/KAThe Sunset Prayer / Davenen Minh/±ah/XX/PR
Iòll let you in on a secret/PR
about how one should pray the sunset prayer./PR
Itòs a juicy bit of praying,/PR
like strolling on grass,/PR
nobodyòs chasing you, nobody hurries you./PR
You walk toward your creator/PR
with gifts in pure, empty hands./PR
The words are golden,/PR
their meaning is transparent,/PR
itòs as though youòre saying them/PR
for the first time./PI/PR
/PR
/PR
/PR
/PL751/XX/PR
If you donòt catch on/PR
that you should feel a little elevated,/PR
youòre not praying the sunset prayer./PR
The tune is sheer simplicity,/PR
youòre just lending a helping hand/PR
to the sinking day./PR
Itòs a heavy responsibility./PR
You take a created day/PR
and you slip it/PR
into the archive of life,/PR
where all our lived-out days are lying together./PR
/PR
The day is departing with a quiet kiss./PR
It lies open at your feet/PR
while you stand saying the blessings./PR
You canòt create anything yourself, but you/PR
can lead the day to its end and see/PR
clearly the smile of its going down./PR
/PR
See how whole it all is,/PR
not diminished for a second,/PR
how you age with the days/PR
that keep dawning,/PR
how you bring your lived-out day/PR
as a gift to eternity./PR
Jacob Glatstein (translated from the Yiddish by Ruth Whitman)/XX/PR
